Sure, here's an example of how to create a parametric keychain with extruded text and a hanging loop in OpenSCAD:

// Define parameters
keychain_width = 50;
keychain_height = 25;
keychain_thickness = 3;
text = "OpenSCAD";
text_size = 8;
text_thickness = 1;
loop_inner_diameter = 5;
loop_outer_diameter = 10;
loop_height = 10;

// Create the keychain base
difference() {
    square([keychain_width, keychain_height], center=true);
    square([keychain_width - 2*keychain_thickness, keychain_height - 2*keychain_thickness], center=true);
}

// Extrude the text
difference() {
    linear_extrude(height=text_thickness) {
        text(text, size=text_size, halign="center");
    }
    square([keychain_width, keychain_height], center=true);
}

// Create the hanging loop
translate([0, -keychain_height/2 + loop_height/2, keychain_thickness/2]) {
    difference() {
        cylinder(h=loop_height, r=loop_outer_diameter/2, center=true);
        cylinder(h=loop_height, r=loop_inner_diameter/2, center=true);
    }
}

You can adjust the parameters at the top of the code to customize the keychain to your liking. To 3D print the keychain, save the code as a .scad file and import it into your preferred slicer program.

Sure, I can help you with that. Here are the general steps to create a Rust command-line tool that scrapes data from a website and saves it to a CSV file using the reqwest and csv libraries:

1. Install the necessary libraries: `reqwest` and `csv`. You can add them to your `Cargo.toml` file as follows:
```
[dependencies]
reqwest = { version = "0.11.4", features = ["blocking", "json"] }
csv = "1.1.6"
```
2. Create a Rust project by running `cargo new scraper` in your terminal. This will create a new directory called `scraper` with the basic structure of a Rust project.

3. Open the `main.rs` file in the `scraper` directory and import the necessary libraries:

```
use std::error::Error;
use csv::Writer;
use reqwest::blocking::get;
```
4. Define the website URL you want to scrape and send a request to it using the `get` function from the `reqwest` library. For example, to scrape the data from the website `https://example.com`, you can write:
```
let url = "https://example.com";
let response = get(url)?;
```
This will send a GET request to the URL and store the response in the `response` variable.

5. Parse the response and extract the data you want to save to the CSV file. You can use the `text` function to get the HTML content of the response and then use a HTML parser library like `scraper` or `select` to extract the relevant data.

6. Create a new CSV file and write the data to it using the `csv` library. You can use the `Writer` struct from the `csv` library to create a new CSV file and write the data to it. For example, to write a single row to the CSV file, you can write:

```
let mut writer = Writer::from_path("data.csv")?;
writer.write_record(&["Column 1", "Column 2", "Column 3"])?;
```
This will create a new file called `data.csv` in the current directory and write the header row to it.

7. Repeat steps 5 and 6 for each set of data you want to save to the CSV file.

8. Build and run the Rust project by running `cargo run` in your terminal. This will compile the project and execute the `main` function, which will scrape the data and save it to the CSV file.

