You can achieve an infinite scroll effect in Vue.js 3 by utilizing the "Intersection Observer" API in combination with Vue's "refs" and "reactive" properties.

First, you'll need to create a "ref" for the element that you want to observe for changes in visibility, in this case, it will be the element that you want to trigger the infinite scroll effect. For example, you can add the following code to your Vue component:

    <template>
    <div class="scroll-container" ref="scrollContainer">
        <!-- Your scrollable content here -->
    </div>
    </template>

    <script>
    import { reactive, ref, onMounted } from 'vue';

    export default {
        setup() {
            const state = reactive({
                page: 1, // The current page
                isIntersecting: false, // Flag to determine if the target element is in view
            });

            const scrollContainer = ref(null); // Create a ref for the scroll container

            const observer = new IntersectionObserver(([entry]) => {
                state.isIntersecting = entry.isIntersecting; // Update the isIntersecting flag
            });

            onMounted(() => {
                observer.observe(scrollContainer.value); // Start observing the scroll container
            });

            // Function to handle the infinite scrolling effect
            const loadMore = () => {
                if (state.isIntersecting) {
                    state.page++; // Increment the current page
                    // Call your API or fetch data here to load more content
                }
            };

            // Add a scroll event listener to the scroll container
            const handleScroll = () => {
                const scrollHeight = scrollContainer.value.scrollHeight;
                const scrollTop = scrollContainer.value.scrollTop;
                const clientHeight = scrollContainer.value.clientHeight;

                // Check if the user has scrolled to the bottom of the container
                if (scrollHeight - scrollTop === clientHeight) {
                    loadMore(); // Trigger the infinite scroll effect
                }
            };

            return {
                scrollContainer,
                handleScroll,
            };
        },
    };
    </script>

In this example, we're creating a "ref" for the scroll container element, and setting up an Intersection Observer to detect when the element comes into view. When the element is in view, we'll update the "isIntersecting" flag.

Next, we add a "scroll" event listener to the scroll container, and check if the user has scrolled to the bottom of the container. If they have, we'll call the "loadMore" function to trigger the infinite scroll effect.

In the "loadMore" function, you can make a call to your API or fetch more data to load into the scrollable content.

